<font color="#FF0000">THE FLOCK DWINDLES</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct 22 20:52:59 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ed,<br><br>
To add insult to injury the service focuses the aviator selection from the academies.  They choose the best and brightest and the ones who pass the most stringent physical.  The so-called creme of the crop.  A lot is invested in their education before they are off to flight school.  Makes them even more appealing to the job market.<br><br>
There are stringent paybacks for the training.  Long service commitments.  Many are only waiting for the time to elapse.  Others lose faith in the system due to the political BS we see today.  They know with the normal wind down of the cold war and the loss of concern about the enemy (a false concern) that the system will turn to other focus.  Current inventory lacks for parts and money.  I see today how they piece together aging assets to meet minimum war reserves.<br><br>
The kids coming through our house are very young even the test pilots.  The old guys just don't seem to be there.<br><br>
Not at all what you remember.  At least the Army is a bit better, but not by much and I do have a bit of experience with the helo group.<br><br>
Saw a flight of 12 gunships today.  Beautiful sight to see them all in a stacked trail formation<br>

